{"title_page": "Stanley, Perthshire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = Scotland\n|official_name = Stanley\n|static_image = Stanley Mills1.jpg\n|static_image_width = 250px\n|static_image_caption = Restored former cotton mill in Stanley, next to the River Tay\n|population = 1,410\n|population_ref = (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.info/php/uk-scotland.php?cityid=S19001195 |title=Stanley (Perth and Kinross, Scotland, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information |website=www.citypopulation.info |access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref>\n|os_grid_reference = NO114328\n|edinburgh_distance_mi = 38\n|london_distance_mi = 369\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.47953|-3.437853|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = Scotland\n|unitary_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Perth and North Perthshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth and North Perthshire]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Perthshire North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Perthshire North]]\n|post_town = Perth\n|postcode_district = PH1\n|postcode_area = PH\n|dial_code = \n}}\n[[File:Stanley Mills, Stanley, Perthshire.jpg|thumb|270px|Stanley Mills, Stanley, Perthshire]]\n[[File:Stanley Church, Perthshire.jpg|thumb|270px|Stanley Church, Perthshire]]\n'''Stanley''' is a village on the north side of the [[River Tay]] in [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]], around {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} north of [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].\n\nThe section of the [[River Tay]] near the village is a popular location for canoeing and fishing.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe village of Stanley gains its name from Lady Amelia Stanley, the daughter of [[James Stanley, 7th Earl of Derby]]. In the 1600s the area around Stanley was part of the estate of [[Earls of Atholl]] and was also the location of [[Inchbervis Castle]]. In 1659 the castle was renamed Stanley House in honour of  the wedding of [[John Murray, 1st Marquess of Atholl]] and Lady Stanley. When the village was built in the 1700s it took the name Stanley after the nearby house.\n\n==History==\n[[John Murray, 4th Duke of Atholl|John Murray, the 4th Duke of Atholl]], decided in the 18th century to harness of the nearby River Tay to power a [[cotton mill]]. [[Richard Arkwright]], an inventor of [[cotton-spinning machinery]] was persuaded by [[George Dempster (lawyer)|George Dempster]] (the local [[Member of Parliament|MP]]), while Dempster was visiting [[Cromford]] in [[Derbyshire]], to come to [[Scotland]] to set up a cotton mill in Stanley as well as one at [[New Lanark]]. Stanley Mills opened in 1787, and by its 10th year employed 350 people.\n\nThe village of Stanley was built to house the workers of the mill. Work on the village began in 1784. It was designed by the Duke of Atholl\u2019s factor [[James Stobie]]. By 1799 the village\u2019s population was around 400, and by 1831 it had reached around 2,000 residents, about 50% of whom worked in the mill.\n\n==Stanley Mill==\nStanley was largely founded to house workers for a huge mill on the banks of the River Tay.\n\nThe mill was originally water-powered but was later converted to steam and finally to electric power. For most of its history it produced cotton thread, but in the 20th century changed to cigarette ribbon.  The Dempster & Co company was established in 1787 by seven men including [[Richard Arkwright]], [[George Dempster (lawyer)|George Dempster]] and [[William Sandeman]] to build the mill on land feued from the Duke of Atholl to provide employment to Highlanders affected by the [[clearances]].<ref>''Perth Entrepreneurs: the Sandemans of Springfield'' by Charles D Waterston, 2008, pages 32\u201333: these pages reference other information sources. {{ISBN|978-0-905452-52-4}}</ref> A fire in 1799 destroyed a large section of the mill and it reopened in 1802, partly with advice from [[David Dale]] of [[New Lanark]] (which it closely resembles).\n\nThe mill used coal gas for lighting until 1921, when this was replaced by a hydroelectric power plant, which was built to also supply electricity to the village.  The power station was closed in 1965 but was reopened in 2003 by [[Npower (United Kingdom)|npower]].\n\nFrom the 1960s the mill was in decline, and it finally closed down in 1989. After that the mill fell derelict. Historic Scotland bought the mill in 1995 and over the next ten years, in liaison with the Phoenix Trust, the buildings renovated and turned into private flats plus a museum depicting life in the 19th century and the story of the mill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historic-scotland.gov.uk/propertyresults/propertyabout.htm?PropID=PL_273&PropName=Stanley+Mills|title=Historic Environment Scotland|website=Historic-scotland.gov.uk|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\n===Train===\nA railway station was built in Stanley in 1848. This later evolved into a junction station, as it lay at the point where the branch line to [[Forfar]] broke off from the [[Highland Main Line]]. The Highland Main Line still runs though the village, but the station was closed in 1956.\n\n===Bus===\nA bus service of Stanley-based Allan & Scott used to run the five miles between Stanley and [[Bankfoot]] twice a day on Sundays in the 1930s. The service was taken over in 1946 by A&C McLennan of Spittalfield. Permission to use [[double decker bus]]es was granted in 1950. In 1952, the fare was 5{{half}} [[shilling]]s single and 10 shillings return, with gradual increases to 8 shillings single and one [[Farthing (British coin)|farthing]] return by 1963. By 1966, the service operated only on the first Sunday of each month. Service was withdrawn in 1967.<ref>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 2 April 2020, p. 28</ref>\n\n==Ballathie House==\n[[Ballathie House]] was built during the 1850s near Stanley. It was built by the Robertson family, the land having originally been owned by the [[Clan Drummond|Drummond family]], the [[Earl of Perth|Earls of Perth]]. Since 1972 it has operated as a country house hotel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.stanleyperthshire.co.uk  Jim Donaldson's Unofficial Stanley Website]\n* [http://www.princes-regeneration.org/bestpractice/stanmills.htm Princes Regeneration Stanley Mills Information]\n* [http://addiator.blogspot.com/2009/06/visit-to-stanley-mills.html A visit to Stanley Mills]\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = Scotland\n|official_name = Stanley\n|static_image = Stanley Mills1.jpg\n|static_image_width = 250px\n|static_image_caption = Restored former cotton mill in Stanley, next to the River Tay\n|population = 1,410\n|population_ref = (2016)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.info/php/uk-scotland.php?cityid=S19001195 |title=Stanley (Perth and Kinross, Scotland, United Kingdom) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information |website=www.citypopulation.info |access-date=7 April 2019}}</ref>\n|os_grid_reference = NO114328\n|edinburgh_distance_mi = 38\n|london_distance_mi = 369\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.47953|-3.437853|display=inline,title}}\n|map_type = Scotland\n|unitary_scotland = [[Perth and Kinross]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Perth and North Perthshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Perth and North Perthshire]]\n|constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Perthshire North (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Perthshire North]]\n|post_town = Perth\n|postcode_district = PH1\n|postcode_area = PH\n|dial_code = \n}}\n[[File:Stanley Mills, Stanley, Perthshire.jpg|thumb|270px|Stanley Mills, Stanley, Perthshire]]\n[[File:Stanley Church, Perthshire.jpg|thumb|270px|Stanley Church, Perthshire]]\n'''Stanley''' is a village on the north side of the [[River Tay]] in [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]], around {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} north of [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]].\n\nThe section of the [[River Tay]] near the village is a popular location for canoeing and fishing.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe village of Stanley gains its name from Lady Amelia Stanley, the daughter of [[James Stanley, 7th Earl of Derby]]. In the 1600s the area around Stanley was part of the estate of [[Earls of Atholl]] and was also the location of [[Inchbervis Castle]]. In 1659 the castle was renamed Stanley House in honour of  the wedding of [[John Murray, 1st Marquess of Atholl]] and Lady Stanley. When the village was built in the 1700s it took the name Stanley after the nearby house.\n\n==History==\n[[John Murray, 4th Duke of Atholl|John Murray, the 4th Duke of Atholl]], decided in the 18th century to harness of the nearby River Tay to power a [[cotton mill]]. [[Richard Arkwright]], an inventor of [[cotton-spinning machinery]] was persuaded by [[George Dempster (lawyer)|George Dempster]] (the local [[Member of Parliament|MP]]), while Dempster was visiting [[Cromford]] in [[Derbyshire]], to come to [[Scotland]] to set up a cotton mill in Stanley as well as one at [[New Lanark]]. Stanley Mills opened in 1787, and by its 10th year employed 350 people.\n\nThe village of Stanley was built to house the workers of the mill. Work on the village began in 1784. It was designed by the Duke of Atholl\u2019s factor [[James Stobie]]. By 1799 the village\u2019s population was around 400, and by 1831 it had reached around 2,000 residents, about 50% of whom worked in the mill.\n\n==Stanley Mill==\nStanley was largely founded to house workers for a huge mill on the banks of the River Tay.\n\nThe mill was originally water-powered but was later converted to steam and finally to electric power. For most of its history it produced cotton thread, but in the 20th century changed to cigarette ribbon.  The Dempster & Co company was established in 1787 by seven men including [[Richard Arkwright]], [[George Dempster (lawyer)|George Dempster]] and [[William Sandeman]] to build the mill on land feued from the Duke of Atholl to provide employment to Highlanders affected by the [[clearances]].<ref>''Perth Entrepreneurs: the Sandemans of Springfield'' by Charles D Waterston, 2008, pages 32\u201333: these pages reference other information sources. {{ISBN|978-0-905452-52-4}}</ref> A fire in 1799 destroyed a large section of the mill and it reopened in 1802, partly with advice from [[David Dale]] of [[New Lanark]] (which it closely resembles).\n\nThe mill used coal gas for lighting until 1921, when this was replaced by a hydroelectric power plant, which was built to also supply electricity to the village.  The power station was closed in 1965 but was reopened in 2003 by [[Npower (United Kingdom)|npower]].\n\nFrom the 1960s the mill was in decline, and it finally closed down in 1989. After that the mill fell derelict. Historic Scotland bought the mill in 1995 and over the next ten years, in liaison with the Phoenix Trust, the buildings renovated and turned into private flats plus a museum depicting life in the 19th century and the story of the mill.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historic-scotland.gov.uk/propertyresults/propertyabout.htm?PropID=PL_273&PropName=Stanley+Mills|title=Historic Environment Scotland|website=Historic-scotland.gov.uk|accessdate=2 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\n===Railway===\nA railway station was built in Stanley in 1848. This later evolved into a junction station, as it lay at the point where the branch line to [[Forfar]] broke off from the [[Highland Main Line]]. The Highland Main Line still runs though the village, but the station was closed in 1956.\n\n===Bus===\nA bus service of Stanley-based Allan & Scott used to run the five miles between Stanley and [[Bankfoot]] twice a day on Sundays in the 1930s. The service was taken over in 1946 by A&C McLennan of Spittalfield. Permission to use [[double decker bus]]es was granted in 1950. In 1952, the fare was 5{{half}} [[shilling]]s single and 10 shillings return, with gradual increases to 8 shillings single and one [[Farthing (British coin)|farthing]] return by 1963. By 1966, the service operated only on the first Sunday of each month. Service was withdrawn in 1967.<ref>''[[The Courier (Dundee)|The Courier]]'', 2 April 2020, p. 28</ref>\n\n==Ballathie House==\n[[Ballathie House]] was built during the 1850s near Stanley. It was built by the Robertson family, the land having originally been owned by the [[Clan Drummond|Drummond family]], the [[Earl of Perth|Earls of Perth]]. Since 1972 it has operated as a country house hotel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.stanleyperthshire.co.uk  Jim Donaldson's Unofficial Stanley Website]\n* [http://www.princes-regeneration.org/bestpractice/stanmills.htm Princes Regeneration Stanley Mills Information]\n* [http://addiator.blogspot.com/2009/06/visit-to-stanley-mills.html A visit to Stanley Mills]\n\n{{Perth & Kinross Towns & Villages}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Perth and Kinross]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRailway", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanley,_Perthshire"}
{"title_page": "Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi", "text_new": "<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi|date=13 February 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|religion         = [[Islam]]\n|honorific_prefix = Mufti, Mawl\u0101na\n|name             = Dr. Muhammad Najeeb Qasmi Sambhali\n|image            = Dr. Najeeb Qasmi receiving memento from previous Indian Cricket Team Captain Mohammad Azharuddin on 8 April 2015.jpg\n|caption          = Qasmi receiving memento from former Indian Cricket Team Captain Mohammad Azharuddin on 8 April 2015\n|alma_mater       = [[Darul Uloom Deoband]], [[Jamia Millia Islamia]], [[Delhi University]]\n|movement = [[Deobandi]]\n|jurisprudence = [[Hanafi]]\n|awards = Watan Ke Ratna Award 2019\n|website = [http://najeebqasmi.com/ najeebqasmi.com]\n}}\n'''Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi Sambhali''' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] Sunni Islamic scholar.<ref name=\"economic\">{{cite web |title=Indian launches Urdu mobile app for Haj pilgrims |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/indian-launches-urdu-mobile-app-for-haj-pilgrims/articleshow/47704916.cms |website=Economic Times |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He is founder of Al-Noor Public School, [[Sambhal]]<ref name=\"khabar\">{{cite web |title=\u201d\u0648\u0637\u0646 \u0633\u0645\u0627\u0686\u0627\u0631\u201c \u0646\u06d2 \u0688\u0627\u06a9\u0679\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u0648 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u06cc \u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062c\u06cc \u062e\u062f\u0645\u0627\u062a \u067e\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0688 \u0633\u06d2 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0632\u0627 |url=http://www.fikrokhabar.com/ur/content-details/53632/news/watan-samachar-dr-najeeb-qasmi.html |website=fikrokhabar |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> and has authored nearly 50 books.\n==Family background==\nMufti Najeeb Qasmi is grandson of Maulana Ismail Sambhali who was a [[muhaddith]] and an activist of the [[Indian Independence movement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/68906|title=Hadith presentation launched in Riyadh|first=Saudi Gazette|last=report|date=16 December 2013|website=Saudigazette}}</ref>\nSambhali was Shaykh al-Hadith at [[Jamia Qasmia Madrasa Shahi, Moradabad]] in India and his students include [[Qazi Athar Mubarakpuri]] and [[Nizamuddin Asir Adrawi]].<ref name=''dastan''>{{Cite book|title=Dastan-e-Natamam|author=[[Asir Adrawi]]|language=Urdu|pages=72,73}}</ref>\n==Education==\nMufti Najeeb Qasmi studied traditional [[dars-e-nizami]] from the [[Darul Uloom Deoband]],<ref name=\"arabnews\">{{cite web |title=Islamic website with extensive library launched |url=https://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/islamic-website-extensive-library-launched |website=arabnews.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and graduated from there in 1994.<ref name=\"circles\">{{cite web |title=Website to highlight the contribution of Ulama of Indian subcontinent |url=http://twocircles.net/2013jan07/website_highlight_contribution_ulama_indian_subcontinent.html |website=twocircles.net |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> He completed his bachelor's degree from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]<ref name=\"digest\">{{cite web |title=Flashes from the Muslim World |url=http://www.youngmuslimdigest.com/news-flashes/05/2013/flashes-from-the-muslim-world-2/ |website=youngmuslimdigest |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and got a masters degree in Arabic from the [[Delhi University]]. Qasmi wrote his PhD thesis on Hadith studies from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref name=\"circles\" />\n==Career==\nQasmi established ''Al-Noor Public School'' in Sambhal, [[Uttar Pradesh]] on 21 December 2018. The foundation stone of the school was laid down by teachers of the [[Darul Uloom Deoband]] and [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fikrokhabar.com/ur/content-details/37602/news/sanbhal.html|title=\u0633\u0646\u0628\u06be\u0644 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u067e\u0628\u0644\u06a9 \u0627\u0633\u06a9\u0648\u0644 \u06a9\u06d2 \u0627\u0641\u062a\u062a\u0627\u062d\u06cc \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0645\u0644\u06a9 \u06a9\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u06cc \u0634\u062e\u0635\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u06a9\u06cc \u0634\u0631\u06a9\u062a|website=FikroKhabar}}</ref>\nQasmi\u2019s articles have appeared in ''Monthly al-Bayyinat'' of [[Jamia Binoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.banuri.edu.pk/web/articles/writer/%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%DB%8C+%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF+%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C+%D8%B3%D9%86%D8%A8%DA%BE%D9%84%DB%8C|title=\u0645\u0636\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0626\u06d2 \u0645\u0641\u062a\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u0633\u0646\u0628\u06be\u0644\u06cc &#124; \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u06c1 \u0628\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646|first=\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u06c1 \u0628\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc|last=\u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646|website=www.banuri.edu.pk}}</ref>\nQasmi's articles also appear on [[The Inquilab]], [[The Munsif Daily]], [[The Siasat Daily]], [[Urdu Times]], [[Avadhnama]] and other Indian and Pakistani newspapers like [[Daily Jang]]<ref name=\"pk\">{{cite web |title=Najeeb Qasmi's articles on Jang.com.pk |url=https://jang.com.pk/search1?q=%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C |website=Jang.com.pk |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Daily Express (Urdu newspaper)|Daily Express]].<ref name=\"express\">{{cite web |title=Articles of Dr Najeeb Qasmi |url=https://www.express.pk/author/2475/doctor-muhammad-najeeb-qasmi-sanbhali/ |website=express.pk |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><br>\n\nNumerous articles of Qasmi have appeared on ''Jahan-e-Urdu''.<ref name=\"urdu\">{{cite web |title=Articles of Qasmi on Jahan-e-Urdu |url=https://www.jahan-e-urdu.com/?s=+%DA%88%D8%A7%DA%A9%D9%B9%D8%B1+%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF+%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C+%D8%B3%D9%86%D8%A8%DA%BE%D9%84%DB%8C |website=jahan-e-urdu.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nQasmi also writes on his website, which was released in a function held in Riyadh<ref name=\"milli\">{{cite web |title=New Islamic website inaugurated in Riyadh |url=http://www.milligazette.com/news/6351-new-islamic-website-inaugurated-in-riyadh |website=milligazette |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> on 4 January 2013 by a number of Indian scholars.<ref name=\"digest\"/><ref name=\"web\">{{cite web |title=New Islamic website launched |url=http://www.bhatkallys.com/gulf/launch-of-a-new-islamic-website-www-najeebislamic-com/ |website=bhatkallys.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Saudi Gazette in its report called the website a brain child of Qasmi.<ref name=\"report\">{{cite news |title=New Islamic Website Launched |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bazmeqalam/nWIdqCSOewU |accessdate=31 March 2020 |agency=Saudi Gazette |date=11 January 2013}}</ref> At the launch program, Qasmi had said that \"Given the popularity of the Internet, many new websites with Islamic names are launched regularly, misinterpreting Islamic teachings. This website provides reliable Islamic content for users\".<ref name=\"arabnews\" />\n\n===Hajj-e-Mabroor===\nQasmi launched Hajj-e-Mabroor application to help provide accurate information about [[Hajj]] and [[Umrah]].<ref name=\"hajj\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Hajj-e-Mabroor\u2019 the new mobile app for Hajj & Umrah |url=http://muslimmirror.com/eng/hajj-e-mabroor-the-new-mobile-app-for-hajj-umrah/ |website=Muslim Mirror |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> It was released in 2015 in by [[Muhammad Mustafa Azmi]] <ref name=\"economic\" /><ref name=\"siasatarchive\">{{cite web |title=Hajj-e-Mabroor app launched in 3 languages |url=https://archive.siasat.com/news/hajj-e-mabroor-app-launched-3-languages-997641/ |website=Siasat.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web |title=Hajj & Umrah Apps Launched |url=https://islamicvoice.com/community-round-up/hajj-umrah-apps-launched/ |website=islamicvoice |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The application has articles, books and videos of Qasmi in English, [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]] covering various aspects of [[Hajj]] and [[Umrah]].<ref name=\"voice\"/><ref name=\"saudigazette1\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Hajj-e-Mabroor\u2019 app launched |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/160637 |website=SaudiGazette |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\nQasmi's set of 38 books was released by [[Muhammad Mustafa Azmi]].<ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite web |title=Set of 38 Islamic books in 3 languages launched |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/151305 |website=saudigazette |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> whilst his 6 books were released in Ansari auditorium of the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] by the former VC of [[Jamia Millia Islamia|JMI]] [[Talat Ahmad]], [[Akhtarul Wasey]] and [[Abul Qasim Nomani]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urdunews.com/node/230371/%DA%A9%D9%85%DB%8C%D9%88%D9%86%D9%B9%DB%8C/%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%DB%81-%D9%85%D9%84%DB%8C%DB%81-%D9%85%DB%8C%DA%BA-%DA%88%D8%A7%DA%A9%D9%B9%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C-%DA%A9%DB%8C-6%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%88%DA%BA-%DA%A9%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1|title=\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0645\u0644\u06cc\u06c1 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0688\u0627\u06a9\u0679\u0631 \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc 6\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u0627 \u0627\u062c\u0631\u0627\u0621 (6 books of Dr Najeeb Qasmi released in Jamia Millia Islamia)|date=9 April 2018|website=Urdu News \u2013 \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648 \u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632}}</ref>\n\nQasmi's books include:\n* Qur\u2019an & Hadith - Main Sources of Islamic Ideology\n*Umrah Ka Tariqah<ref name=\"umrah\">{{cite web |author1=Mufti Najeeb Qasmi |title=Umrah Ka Tariqah |url=https://archive.org/download/UmrahKaTariqah/Umrah%20Ka%20Tariqah.pdf |website=Archive.org |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=Urdu}}</ref>\n* Islahi Mazameen (released by [[Akhtarul Wasey]])\n* Dars-e-Quran<ref name=\"khabar\" />\n*Dars-e-Hadith<ref name=\"khabar\" />\n* Journey to Madina<ref name=\"madina\">{{cite web |title=Video, AudioBook, eBook: Journey to Madina \u2013 Dr. Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi (English) |url=https://theclearevidence.org/aspects-of-life/madina/video-ebook-journey-to-madina-dr-mohammad-najeeb-qasmi-english/ |website=TheClearEvidence.org |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Watan Ke Ratna Award 2019<ref name=\"dastan\">{{cite web|title=A Tribute to Maulana Azad|url=http://urdu.watansamachar.com/A-true-tribute-to-Maulana-Azad-promoting-Hindu-Muslim-unity-and-education-tariq-anwar-watan-samachar-fouram|website=WatanSamachar.com |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n==Reflections==\nPadma Shri [[Akhtarul Wasey]] said about Qasmi that: \"I often read his electronic articles.  His moderate and scholarly articles always touch me. I express my gratitude to  Maulana Najeeb Qasmi and pray for his long life to Allah\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Knowledge and Remembrance|chapter=Reflections and Testimonials|publisher=Freedom  Fighter Maulana  Ismail Sambhali  Welfare|editor=Adnan Mahmood Qasmi|page=xiii}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Muhammad Mustafa Al-A'zami]]\n* [[Darul Uloom Deoband]]\n* [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://najeebqasmi.com Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi Sambhali - Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qasmi, Mohammad Najeeb}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sambhal district]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Islamic studies scholars]]\n[[Category:Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Indian Sunni Muslim scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Indian scholars of Islam]]\n[[Category:Deobandis]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi|date=13 February 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|religion         = [[Islam]]\n|honorific_prefix = Mufti, Mawl\u0101na\n|name             = Dr. Muhammad Najeeb Qasmi Sambhali\n|image            = Dr. Najeeb Qasmi receiving memento from previous Indian Cricket Team Captain Mohammad Azharuddin on 8 April 2015.jpg\n|caption          = Qasmi receiving memento from former Indian Cricket Team Captain Mohammad Azharuddin on 8 April 2015\n|alma_mater       = [[Darul Uloom Deoband]], [[Jamia Millia Islamia]], [[Delhi University]]\n|movement = [[Deobandi]]\n|jurisprudence = [[Hanafi]]\n|awards = Watan Ke Ratna Award 2019\n|website = [http://najeebqasmi.com/ najeebqasmi.com]\n}}\n'''Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi Sambhali''' is an [[Indian people|Indian]] Sunni Islamic scholar.<ref name=\"economic\">{{cite web |title=Indian launches Urdu mobile app for Haj pilgrims |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/indian-launches-urdu-mobile-app-for-haj-pilgrims/articleshow/47704916.cms |website=Economic Times |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> He is founder of Al-Noor Public School, [[Sambhal]]<ref name=\"khabar\">{{cite web |title=\u201d\u0648\u0637\u0646 \u0633\u0645\u0627\u0686\u0627\u0631\u201c \u0646\u06d2 \u0688\u0627\u06a9\u0679\u0631 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u0648 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u06cc \u0648\u0633\u0645\u0627\u062c\u06cc \u062e\u062f\u0645\u0627\u062a \u067e\u0631 \u0627\u06cc\u0648\u0627\u0631\u0688 \u0633\u06d2 \u0646\u0648\u0627\u0632\u0627 |url=http://www.fikrokhabar.com/ur/content-details/53632/news/watan-samachar-dr-najeeb-qasmi.html |website=fikrokhabar |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> and has authored nearly 50 books.\n==Family background==\nMufti Najeeb Qasmi is grandson of Maulana Ismail Sambhali who was a [[muhaddith]] and an activist of the [[Indian Independence movement]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/68906|title=Hadith presentation launched in Riyadh|first=Saudi Gazette|last=report|date=16 December 2013|website=Saudigazette}}</ref>\nSambhali was Shaykh al-Hadith at [[Jamia Qasmia Madrasa Shahi, Moradabad]] in India and his students include [[Qazi Athar Mubarakpuri]] and [[Nizamuddin Asir Adrawi]].<ref name=''dastan''>{{Cite book|title=Dastan-e-Natamam|author=[[Asir Adrawi]]|language=Urdu|pages=72,73}}</ref>\n==Education==\nMufti Najeeb Qasmi studied traditional [[dars-e-nizami]] from the [[Darul Uloom Deoband]],<ref name=\"arabnews\">{{cite web |title=Islamic website with extensive library launched |url=https://www.arabnews.com/saudi-arabia/islamic-website-extensive-library-launched |website=arabnews.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and graduated from there in 1994.<ref name=\"circles\">{{cite web |title=Website to highlight the contribution of Ulama of Indian subcontinent |url=http://twocircles.net/2013jan07/website_highlight_contribution_ulama_indian_subcontinent.html |website=twocircles.net |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> He completed his bachelor's degree from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]<ref name=\"digest\">{{cite web |title=Flashes from the Muslim World |url=http://www.youngmuslimdigest.com/news-flashes/05/2013/flashes-from-the-muslim-world-2/ |website=youngmuslimdigest |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and got a masters degree in Arabic from the [[Delhi University]]. Qasmi wrote his PhD thesis on Hadith studies from the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref name=\"circles\" />\n==Career==\nQasmi established ''Al-Noor Public School'' in Sambhal, [[Uttar Pradesh]] on 21 December 2018. The foundation stone of the school was laid down by teachers of the [[Darul Uloom Deoband]] and [[Jamia Millia Islamia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fikrokhabar.com/ur/content-details/37602/news/sanbhal.html|title=\u0633\u0646\u0628\u06be\u0644 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u067e\u0628\u0644\u06a9 \u0627\u0633\u06a9\u0648\u0644 \u06a9\u06d2 \u0627\u0641\u062a\u062a\u0627\u062d\u06cc \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0645\u0644\u06a9 \u06a9\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u06cc \u0634\u062e\u0635\u06cc\u0627\u062a \u06a9\u06cc \u0634\u0631\u06a9\u062a|website=FikroKhabar}}</ref>\nQasmi\u2019s articles have appeared in ''Monthly al-Bayyinat'' of [[Jamia Binoria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.banuri.edu.pk/web/articles/writer/%D9%85%D9%81%D8%AA%DB%8C+%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF+%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C+%D8%B3%D9%86%D8%A8%DA%BE%D9%84%DB%8C|title=\u0645\u0636\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u0646 \u0628\u0631\u0627\u0626\u06d2 \u0645\u0641\u062a\u06cc \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u0633\u0646\u0628\u06be\u0644\u06cc &#124; \u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u06c1 \u0628\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc \u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646|first=\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u06c1 \u0628\u0646\u0648\u0631\u06cc|last=\u0679\u0627\u0624\u0646|website=www.banuri.edu.pk}}</ref>\nQasmi's articles also appear on [[The Inquilab]], [[The Munsif Daily]], [[The Siasat Daily]], [[Urdu Times]], [[Avadhnama]] and other Indian and Pakistani newspapers like [[Daily Jang]]<ref name=\"pk\">{{cite web |title=Najeeb Qasmi's articles on Jang.com.pk |url=https://jang.com.pk/search1?q=%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C |website=Jang.com.pk |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Daily Express (Urdu newspaper)|Daily Express]].<ref name=\"express\">{{cite web |title=Articles of Dr Najeeb Qasmi |url=https://www.express.pk/author/2475/doctor-muhammad-najeeb-qasmi-sanbhali/ |website=express.pk |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><br>\n\nNumerous articles of Qasmi have appeared on ''Jahan-e-Urdu''.<ref name=\"urdu\">{{cite web |title=Articles of Qasmi on Jahan-e-Urdu |url=https://www.jahan-e-urdu.com/?s=+%DA%88%D8%A7%DA%A9%D9%B9%D8%B1+%D9%85%D8%AD%D9%85%D8%AF+%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8+%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C+%D8%B3%D9%86%D8%A8%DA%BE%D9%84%DB%8C |website=jahan-e-urdu.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nQasmi also writes on his website, which was released in a function held in Riyadh<ref name=\"milli\">{{cite web |title=New Islamic website inaugurated in Riyadh |url=http://www.milligazette.com/news/6351-new-islamic-website-inaugurated-in-riyadh |website=milligazette |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> on 4 January 2013 by a number of Indian scholars.<ref name=\"digest\"/><ref name=\"web\">{{cite web |title=New Islamic website launched |url=http://www.bhatkallys.com/gulf/launch-of-a-new-islamic-website-www-najeebislamic-com/ |website=bhatkallys.com |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Saudi Gazette in its report called the website a brain child of Qasmi.<ref name=\"report\">{{cite news |title=New Islamic Website Launched |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/bazmeqalam/nWIdqCSOewU |accessdate=31 March 2020 |agency=Saudi Gazette |date=11 January 2013}}</ref> At the launch program, Qasmi had said that \"Given the popularity of the Internet, many new websites with Islamic names are launched regularly, misinterpreting Islamic teachings. This website provides reliable Islamic content for users\".<ref name=\"arabnews\" />\n\n===Hajj-e-Mabroor===\nQasmi launched Hajj-e-Mabroor application to help provide accurate information about Hajj and Umrah.<ref name=\"hajj\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Hajj-e-Mabroor\u2019 the new mobile app for Hajj & Umrah |url=http://muslimmirror.com/eng/hajj-e-mabroor-the-new-mobile-app-for-hajj-umrah/ |website=Muslim Mirror |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> It was released in 2015 in by [[Muhammad Mustafa Azmi]] <ref name=\"economic\" /><ref name=\"siasatarchive\">{{cite web |title=Hajj-e-Mabroor app launched in 3 languages |url=https://archive.siasat.com/news/hajj-e-mabroor-app-launched-3-languages-997641/ |website=Siasat.com |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"voice\">{{cite web |title=Hajj & Umrah Apps Launched |url=https://islamicvoice.com/community-round-up/hajj-umrah-apps-launched/ |website=islamicvoice |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> The application has articles, books and videos of Qasmi in English, [[Hindi]] and [[Urdu]] covering various aspects of Hajj and Umrah.<ref name=\"voice\"/><ref name=\"saudigazette1\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Hajj-e-Mabroor\u2019 app launched |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/160637 |website=SaudiGazette |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Literary works==\nQasmi's set of 38 books was released by [[Muhammad Mustafa Azmi]].<ref name=\"gazette\">{{cite web |title=Set of 38 Islamic books in 3 languages launched |url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/151305 |website=saudigazette |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> whilst his 6 books were released in Ansari auditorium of the [[Jamia Millia Islamia]] by the former VC of [[Jamia Millia Islamia|JMI]] [[Talat Ahmad]], [[Akhtarul Wasey]] and [[Abul Qasim Nomani]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urdunews.com/node/230371/%DA%A9%D9%85%DB%8C%D9%88%D9%86%D9%B9%DB%8C/%D8%AC%D8%A7%D9%85%D8%B9%DB%81-%D9%85%D9%84%DB%8C%DB%81-%D9%85%DB%8C%DA%BA-%DA%88%D8%A7%DA%A9%D9%B9%D8%B1-%D9%86%D8%AC%DB%8C%D8%A8-%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85%DB%8C-%DA%A9%DB%8C-6%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%88%DA%BA-%DA%A9%D8%A7-%D8%A7%D8%AC%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1|title=\u062c\u0627\u0645\u0639\u06c1 \u0645\u0644\u06cc\u06c1 \u0645\u06cc\u06ba \u0688\u0627\u06a9\u0679\u0631 \u0646\u062c\u06cc\u0628 \u0642\u0627\u0633\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc 6\u06a9\u062a\u0627\u0628\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u0627 \u0627\u062c\u0631\u0627\u0621 (6 books of Dr Najeeb Qasmi released in Jamia Millia Islamia)|date=9 April 2018|website=Urdu News \u2013 \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648 \u0646\u06cc\u0648\u0632}}</ref>\n\nQasmi's books include:\n* Qur\u2019an & Hadith - Main Sources of Islamic Ideology\n*Umrah Ka Tariqah<ref name=\"umrah\">{{cite web |author1=Mufti Najeeb Qasmi |title=Umrah Ka Tariqah |url=https://archive.org/download/UmrahKaTariqah/Umrah%20Ka%20Tariqah.pdf |website=Archive.org |accessdate=31 May 2019 |language=Urdu}}</ref>\n* Islahi Mazameen (released by [[Akhtarul Wasey]])\n* Dars-e-Quran<ref name=\"khabar\" />\n*Dars-e-Hadith<ref name=\"khabar\" />\n* Journey to Madina<ref name=\"madina\">{{cite web |title=Video, AudioBook, eBook: Journey to Madina \u2013 Dr. Mohammad Najeeb Qasmi (English) |url=https://theclearevidence.org/aspects-of-life/madina/video-ebook-journey-to-madina-dr-mohammad-najeeb-qasmi-english/ |website=TheClearEvidence.org |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Watan Ke Ratna Award 2019<ref name=\"dastan\">{{cite web|title=A Tribute to Maulana Azad|url=http://urdu.watansamachar.com/A-true-tribute-to-Maulana-Azad-promoting-Hindu-Muslim-unity-and-education-tariq-anwar-watan-samachar-fouram|website=WatanSamachar.com |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n==Reflections==\nPadma Shri [[Akhtarul Wasey]] said about Qasmi that: \"I often read his electronic articles.  His moderate and scholarly articles always touch me. I express my gratitude to  Maulana Najeeb Qasmi and pray for his long life to Allah\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Knowledge and Remembrance|chapter=Reflections and Testimonials|publisher=Freedom  Fighter Maulana  Ismail Sambhali  Welfare|editor=Adnan Mahmood Qasmi|page=xiii}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Muhammad Mustafa Al-A'zami]]\n* [[Darul Uloom Deoband]]\n* [[Jamia Millia Islamia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== 